TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Model of CEO Dismissal
AU  - Fredrickson, James W.
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
AU  - Baumrin, Sara
Y1  - 1988/04/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4306882
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1988.4306882
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 255
EP  - 270
VL  - 13
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A model is presented in which social and political factors are used to predict the likelihood of a CEO's dismissal. Although an organization's performance affects dismissal of a CEO, it is argued that the link is not direct. It is mediated by four constructs: (a) the board of directors' expectations and attributions, (b) the board's allegiances and values, (c) the availability of alternative candidates for CEO, and (d) the power of the incumbent CEO. Observable determinants of these constructs are identified It is suggested that these determinants can be found in characteristics of the board, the organization, the industry, the CEO, and the CEO's predecessor.
AB  - A model is presented in which social and political factors are used to predict the likelihood of a CEO's dismissal. Although an organization's performance affects dismissal of a CEO, it is argued that the link is not direct. It is mediated by four constructs: (a) the board of directors' expectations and attributions, (b) the board's allegiances and values, (c) the availability of alternative candidates for CEO, and (d) the power of the incumbent CEO. Observable determinants of these constructs are identified It is suggested that these determinants can be found in characteristics of the board, the organization, the industry, the CEO, and the CEO's predecessor.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1988.4306882
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1988.4306882
Y2  - 2026/04/24
